Though force is not always needed by police, the skills, resources, and knowledge used by the military to subdue enemies may translate into police use and management when it is needed. This quality sets the police apart from other state institutions like public schools. Indeed, Bittner's (1970) assessment of policing posits that the use of force is the distinguishing hallmark of police work compared to other state institutions and has natural connections to military work.
[T]here exist apparent analogies between the military and the police and it does not seem to be wholly unwarranted to expect methods of internal organization that work in one context to work also in the other. Both institutions are instruments of force and for both institutions the occasions for using force are unpredictably distributed. Thus, the personnel in each must be kept in a highly disciplined state of alert preparedness. The formalism that characterizes military organization, the insistence on rules and regulations, on spit and polish, on obedience to superiors, and so on, constitute a permanent rehearsal for “the real thing.” (Bittner, 1970, p. 53)
As Bittner alludes, there are practical reasons for police work to emulate military practices of command, discipline, and readiness. Contemporarily, Bittner's insight is supported by Collins's (2009, 2008) arguments that humans left to their own devices are historically bad at using violence competently but have learned to use ritualistic training provided by institutions charged with exercising the state's monopoly on violence to learn how to use force competently. Thus, while soldiers drill and learn to submit to hierarchy in order to advance under enemy fire (quite the unnatural response), some police train to quickly subdue dangerous persons, and elite police units may prepare for extreme violence in mass shootings and hostage situations. In both the military and police realms of work, shared practices like uniforms, drills, inspections, deference to authority, and following a chain of command have proven to be effective ways for humans to use violence to achieve some goal: the “real thing” that Bittner (1970) alludes to.
While not all challenges to social order addressed by the police necessitate the use of violence, the police remain the one domestic organization that may resort to violence to implement order. As arbiters of the state's violence monopoly, it is rational for the police to seek tried and true methods to efficiently use violence to eliminate any challenges to the state and social order (Tilly, 1985). As such, Kraska (2007) states it is “obvious that the police since their inception have been to some extent ‘militarized’” and that “the real concern when discerning police militarization is … the extent to which a civilian police body is militarized”(p, 503, emphasis added). Kraska suggests that a continuous concept of militarization in police work allows for an understanding of police work as having some inherent degree of militarization yet still possessing ordinal traits. To identify this more continuous concept, Kraska argues that police militarization can be understood as engaging in an ideology of militarism defined as “a set of beliefs, values, and assumptions that stress the use of force and threat of violence as the most appropriate and efficacious means to solve problems” (Kraska, 2007, p. 503).
Relying on this definition of militarism, Kraska (2007) conceptualizes police militarization as a process of police “arming, organizing, planning, training for, threatening, and sometimes implementing violent conflict” (p. 503). This process of militarization can occur along four different dimensions of police work. The first is a material dimension, where police adopt weapons and equipment that enable them to deploy violence effectively. Second, militarization occurs along a cultural dimension, where police adopt militaristic values, appearances, and language. Third, there is an organizational dimension, where police employees are managed along a military hierarchy and/or into elite squads. And the fourth is an operational dimension, where police work is conducted aggressively and in a military fashion, including the use of military equipment to conduct ordinary police work (Kraska, 2007). Together, these four dimensions of police militarization provide a continuum for measuring police militarization, whereas prior to Kraska, scholars had given little thought to these distinctions, discussing them inconsistently as “paramilitarization,” “paramilitarism,” or just “militarization” with (Hill & Beger, 2009; Kappeler & Kraska, 2015; Waddington, 1987). Kraska's conceptualization of police militarization has since become the standard for police militarization scholars.
Understanding militarism in police work likens the police to the military because police can use violence and prepare for its use in the training, practice, organization, and culture of policing. Whether or not the police actually use

