3 | NORMATIVE DEBATES ON POLICE MILITARIZATION
Americans are rather amiable toward the metaphor of war in civil society, with government waging “wars” on poverty, crime, drugs, and terrorism (Simon, 2007). Following the metaphor of a “war on crime,” is it possible that police militarization simply makes the police better able to wage such a war? Or are there dangers to civil society when police engage with militarism? Some have argued that militarization is a progressive effort to professionalize police work (Cowper, 2000; den Heyer, 2014) and that increased militarism in police work improves the police's capacity to protect the public (Waddington, 1987, 1993). Scholars sympathetic to the idea that militarization improves the efficacy of police work generally argue that (1) police militarization increases the police's ability to use force but does not inherently result in excessive use of force and (2) militarization is a natural progression in the professionalization of police work.
Regarding the first point, Waddington (1987, 1993) argues that militarization enables police to maintain law and order by allowing police to use force more efficiently so that the minimum amount of violence needed can be applied to produce social control. Waddington's argument relies on a historical discussion of police forces using military tactics and militaristic police units (e.g., gendarmeries) to deescalated violent confrontations from rioters who dispersed once met with a well‐equipped and trained police force. Second is the argument that militarization merely reflects police professionalization. Cowper (2000) suggests a wrong‐headed notion of the military model proliferated as a byproduct of military stereotypes from the Vietnam‐era U.S. military as police administrators applied a military model over‐emphasizing a top‐down hierarchy and that modern military practices are more flexible and competent than many laypeople assume. Cowper argues that emulating a modern military model of leadership and management results in an emphasis on teamwork, intelligence building, and learning from historical examples of leadership to improve police competency and professionalism. Citing the need for police professionalization via militarization, Cowper notes:
without dramatic improvement in the tactical and strategic organization of American law enforcement agencies, a reliance on armed military units to supplement police could be an inevitable result. As such we should study and adopt the particular organizational and operational doctrines and methodologies that the military has developed and are applicable to our profession. (Cowper, 2000, p. 243)
Similarly, taking issue with the idea that elite police units using military tactics and equipment is a negative reflection of militarization, den Heyer (2014) argues that such practices instead reflect a “natural progression in the evolution and professionalization” (p. 347) of police work. Put another way, these arguments suggest traditional police forces are unable to deal with increasing crime threats, so rather than turn to the military for help, police need to emulate the aspects of the military that will improve their efficacy.
Perhaps unsurprisingly, arguments endorsing police militarization draw challenges from skeptics almost immediately after they are stated. Waddington's arguments have been consistently challenged (Jefferson, 1987, 1993; Kraska, 1999), as have Cowper's (Buerger, 2000) and den Heyer's (Kappeler & Kraska, 2015). The strongest critique leveled against arguments for police militarization is the lack of rigorous empirical data analyses demonstrating that militarism is inherent to professionalism and improved police efficacy. Many of the arguments made by Cowper

