(2000) and den Heyer (2014) rely on normative assumptions of professionalism and personal anecdotes with little in terms of empirical analysis to support their claims. Kappeler and Kraska's (2015) rebuttal conveys the sentiment, stating that the notion of police militarization as “a natural and inevitable outgrowth of some unaccounted for telos of ‘police professionalism’ is little more than crass historicism that can be used to justify any transformation in the police institution” (p. 2).
Skeptics of police militarization also challenge the idea that police militarization will not inherently increase police use of force because militarism may alter the very nature of police work to prioritize public compliance with legal authority (Jefferson, 1987, 1993). Put another way, while it may be that police militarization may not result in a more violent police force, it might incentivize police to apply a militarism ideology to aspects of police work that did not previously rely on force to solve problems (e.g., the use of SWAT teams to serve low‐risk warrants) (Kappeler & Kraska, 2015; Phillips, 2018). Other empirical work on police units using military equipment and tactics suggests that militarization inspires police to use more violent solutions to problems that did not require them in the past (Balko, 2013; Delehanty, Mewhirter, Welch, & Wilks, 2017; Kappeler & Kraska, 1998, 2015; Lawson, 2018). In his critique of Cowper (2000), Buerger (2000) cautions against a militarism ideology in all areas of police work by arguing that, in terms of goals, police work rarely aligns with the military. Buerger states: “In policing, there is no hill to be taken, no territory to be gained and controlled, only an endless swell of human misery and debauchery to be quelled or controlled. The clarity of win and lose that attends the military occupation will forever elude policing” (p. 453). Thus, applying militarism to police work does not intuitively translate into increased efficacy in police work such as order‐maintenance calls.
Despite skepticism from some scholars, many practitioners and politicians continue to view police militarization as a progressive step in police work (Campbell & Campbell, 2009). According to Phillips (2016), institutional myths about police work being inherently involved in fighting wars on crime, drugs, and terrorism (Simon, 2007) make it difficult to persuade policymakers and police alike that militarization could be a problem. At the same time, Kraska (1999) notes that militarization is not completely without merit as “specialized use of force units housed in larger departments reacting to the rare hostage/terrorist/barricaded suspect situations are a ‘necessary evil’” (p. 153). Here we find a tenuous link between these opposing sides in the normative debate of police militarization. Those arguing police militarization is a non‐problem have little evidence to support the idea that militarization is an objectively benign phenomenon of professionalization, or how it can improve policing outside a reliance on force. At the same time, those skeptical of police militarization recognize that militarization can have a justified role in police work (but, as with all things, in moderation) while also trying to convince a public and political leadership that militarism in police work is not a one‐size‐fits‐all solution for social order. What remains open in this debate, however, is an agreement as to what is the driving force behind police militarization and its impact on criminal justice outcomes. To that end, we now turn our discussion to more empirical matters of social science research findings on police militarization.

4 | EMPIRICAL STUDIES OF POLICE MILITARIZATION
Due to the dearth of data on police militarization (especially compared to other areas of criminal justice research able to draw from large databases like the Uniform Crime Reports or National Crime Victimization Survey), researchers of police militarization have drawn on a wide range of analytic strategies. Much of this work on police militarization has focused on institutional surveys of LEA operations and organization, public surveys, ethnographic studies, experiments, and ecological studies using government data on the acquisition of military equipment. Taken together, these empirical approaches provide a foundation for what police militarization looks like in the United States. In this final section, we offer a concise review of these studies as three broad groups: survey‐based studies, qualitative and experimental studies, and ecological studies. In doing so, we hope to offer a synthesis of what is known in empirical research, what is unknown, and what implications exist for future research.

