4.1 | Survey‐based studies of police militarization

Survey research on police militarization has focused on three areas: the creation and deployment of elite tactical police units (e.g., paramilitary police units (PPUs) (Kraska & Cubellis, 1997; Kraska & Kappeler, 1997)), the views of law enforcement officers regarding police militarization (Kunselman, Vito, & Walsh, 2013; Phillips, 2018; Turner & Fox, 2017), and determinants of public perceptions toward police militarization (Fox, Moule, & Parry, 2018; Lockwood, Doyle, & Comiskey, 2018; Moule, Burruss, Parry, & Fox, 2018; Moule, Fox, & Parry, 2018; Moule, Parry, & Fox, 2018).
Some of the most influential work on police militarization has focused on the creation of elite PPUs trained to use military equipment and in military tactics. Kraska and Cubellis (1997) identify three distinguishing characteristics that differentiate these PPUs from more conventional police forces. One, PPUs train and operate as militaristic units with militaristic command and discipline. Two, PPUs are primarily called upon to use force and can do so either reactively (such as responding to a hostage situation) or proactively (such as a no‐knock raid). Three, PPUs operate under legitimate state authorities (i.e., they are not informal militias). Following this definition, several surveys provide descriptive accounts regarding the use of PPUs by police departments in the United States and rely on PPUs as an indicator for police militarization.
Stevens and MacKenna (1988) conducted the first assessment of PPU prevalence in the United States and received 186 responses from 456 LEAs (a 41% response rate) serving cities with populations of at least 50,000 residents. While Stevens and MacKenna did not ask how often PPUs were deployed or when they were created, they did find that over 90% of their responding departments reported having a PPU. A large majority of responding LEA leaders also indicated that they thought state and federal governments should provide more financial support to LEAs to support their PPUs as these units were expensive to create and maintain.
Kraska and colleagues used two different surveys, one of LEAs in jurisdictions with 25,000 to 50,000 residents (Kraska & Cubellis, 1997) and another of LEAs in jurisdictions with more than 50,000 (Kraska & Kappeler, 1997). Although they are now over 20 years old, these studies have become perhaps the defining assessment of PPU proliferation across the United States. In their study of LEAs in smaller jurisdictions, Kraska and Cubellis (1997) garnered a 72% response rate from LEAs with less than 100 police officers (n = 473) and found that 65% of responding LEAs had a PPU while another 28% planned to create one in a few years. These small LEAs were also most likely to use PPUs in serving search and arrest warrants via no‐knock raids, with 40% of existing PPUs in 1980 participating in warrant work and increasing to 94% of PPUs in 1995. Kraska and Cubellis's emphasis on examining smaller LEAs showed that the creation of PPUs was not limited to just large and well‐resourced LEAs and that once these PPUs were created, they were increasingly likely to be used in day‐to‐day police work. In the second survey, Kraska and Kappeler (1997) found that, in 1982, 59% of LEAs in large jurisdictions had a PPU and that this percentage increased to 89% by 1995. In both studies, Kraska and colleagues conducted follow‐up interviews with LEA administrators to gain insight into how these PPUs were operated and trained. They found that LEA leadership often viewed PPU officers as elite members of the LEA and favored the militaristic training that these PPUs received and that most of these PPUs were being used most often to prosecute the war on drugs (Kraska & Cubellis, 1997; Kraska & Kappeler, 1997). To date, these surveys have not been replicated to update the findings of Kraska and colleagues on the prevalence and use of PPUs, but investigative reports have found PPUs have likely become more common in local LEAs as well as in federal regulatory agencies like the Food and Drug Administration and the Department of Education (Balko, 2013).
Phillips (2018) provides the most recent assessment of PPUs in LEAs in the United States by using a survey of 370 management‐level police (i.e., managers, supervisors, and chiefs), from across the United States who were attending the Federal Bureau of Investigation's National Academy. While this survey of police officers is limited in size and representation compared to earlier large institutional surveys, it provides a much‐needed update to the older surveys. Phillips found that nearly 87% of the police surveyed reported having either an in‐house PPU in their own LEAs or a regionally based PPU they could call upon. Phillips also asked in this survey about training sources for PPUs and found that 83% of respondents said their PPUs trained more than once a month and that many PPUS received

