training from a wide range of sources, including state tactical associations, Federal agencies, private instructors, military personnel, and from their own LEA. In general, LEAs with more employees and resources reported having dedicated PPUs and provided more training opportunities (Phillips, 2018).
Other survey‐based inquiries of police militarization have focused on law enforcement attitudes toward police militarization. Kunselman et al. (2013) surveyed 48 LEA administrators enrolled in a university‐level training course on whether or not they agreed with military management principles in law enforcement work and found that administrators valued militaristic management principles that reinforced hierarchical authority and discouraged flexibility by subordinates. Turner and Fox (2017) surveyed 279 police officers, 161 police administrators, and 25 members of Congress on attitudes regarding police militarization and found that attitudes were divergent between policymakers and police. Specifically, while police officers and administrators were more likely to support a wide range of police militarization issues (e.g., the use of PPUs, the acquisition of military weapons and transportation, and generic “support for militarization”), members of Congress exhibited less support for such issues. Combined with recent public opinion polling on police issues that shows 54% of Americans feel the use of military weapons by police goes “too far” (Ekins, 2016), it seems reasonable to speculate that members of the police are overall more supportive of police militarization than are the general public and policymakers.
Related to police perceptions, Phillips's (2018) survey also asked police officers whether media reporting on police militarization in the wake of the Ferguson unrest impacted how their LEAs used PPUs. Seventy‐eight percent of police surveyed said that their LEAs did not change how often they were used in reaction to events like barricaded suspects, building/area searches, and civilian rescues in response to media coverage of police militarization. More than 65% said that their LEAs did not change how often their PPUs were used for more proactive events like warrant searches. Phillips also asked these police officers how they personally felt about the frequency of PPU use and found that police were generally supportive of PPUs being used more often than their LEA had been using them after Ferguson. In follow‐up interviews with police chiefs and PPU officers, Phillips found that both groups often blamed the media for the “misinformed” public perception of police militarization. Several officers reported that LEAs could do a better job of explaining to the public why military equipment and PPUs improved police efficacy and public safety, while also acknowledging though that some LEAs misused or did not need such equipment.
Finally, researchers have also used surveys to begin assessing public opinion and perceptions regarding police militarization. Lockwood et al. (2018) used a nationally representative survey of 1005 people to examine what characteristics might explain support for police use of military equipment in counterterrorism, drug enforcement, gang enforcement, and riot control. Results indicate that race was not a strong predictor of support or opposition for police using military equipment, while having a college education and being politically liberal were associated with opposing police use of military equipment. Concerns about crime and public safety and satisfaction with local police were positively associated with support for police using military equipment. George Burruss, Bryanna Fox, Richard Moule Jr., and Megan Parry provide a similar assessment of public perceptions of police militarization using an online, nationally representative, survey of 702 individuals; these researchers provide the first insights into how perceptions of police legitimacy and legal cynicism might inform public perceptions and support of police militarization (Fox et al., 2018; Moule, Burruss, et al., 2018; Moule, Fox, & Parry, 2018; Moule, Parry, & Fox, 2018). Fox et al. (2018) used a latent class analysis to find that public support for or opposition against police militarization fell into several distinct categories that were marked by normative beliefs. Specifically, Fox et al. found that people who strongly believed in the legitimacy of the local police and trusted the federal government supported police militarization in general, while those who did not believe in the legitimacy of the local police and distrusted the federal government were not supportive of police militarization. Similar to Lockwood et al.'s findings, racial demographics did not inform what group respondents fell into regarding support for police militarization, but race did help inform subgroups within the groups of supporters or opposers of police militarization one might belong to.
Using OLS regression analyses to assess public opinion from the same survey, Moule, Fox, and Parry (2018) found that respondents who reported higher views of police legitimacy were more likely to support police militarization and feel that the police had not become too militarized, while respondents who reported higher levels of legal cynicism

