clearly demonstrate that perceptions of legitimacy matter for support of police militarization, it remains unknown how actual levels of police militarization might influence perceptions of police legitimacy.

4.2 | Qualitative and experimental studies of police militarization
While survey‐based research demonstrated the proliferation of PPUs, as well as law enforcement support for police militarization in the United States, qualitative studies of police work have examined the cultural influence of militarism in police work. Similarly, there have been a few experimental studies to show how police militarization can influence public perceptions and police efficacy overall. Kraska's (1996) ethnographic work on militaristic training among PPUs emphasizes the importance of masculinity and violence in police militarization. Specifically, Kraska notes that as local, state, and federal governments in the United States increasingly used war metaphors in crime control and drug law enforcement, police increasingly saw themselves as warriors as opposed to public servants. These warrior roles emulate hypermasculine traits that emphasize dominance over perceived threats, real or imagined. Consequently, Kraska traces the roots of police militarization to traditional masculine norms relying on violence to solve social problems in the United States (Gibson, 1994) that have been influential in law enforcement and policy as the state continues to use war‐fighting metaphors in governance (Simon, 2007).
In a second ethnographic study, Kraska and Paulsen (1997) examine the practices of PPUs in “Pleasantville,” with a LEA employing 300+ police officers. Using a grounded theory approach, Kraska and Paulsen found that the culture of police work in the Pleasantville LEA glorified and rewarded members of the PPU with a status as genuine crime fighters. Members of the LEA and the PPU seemed to value military training that came with PPU participation while also sharing an agreement that PPU members faced incredibly dangerous situations on a regular basis, a perception Kraska and Paulsen are skeptical of and more recently Phillips (2016, 2018) documents as more myth than fact. Taken together, these qualitative studies by Kraska and Paulsen (Kraska, 1996; Kraska & Paulsen, 1997) suggest that the influence of militarization in police work goes much deeper than the creation and increased use of PPUs. Militarization appears to mesh seamlessly with the politically conservative orientations held by many police officers and administrators and incentivizes the practice of militaristic values often lauded in police work regardless of their actual efficacy.
While these ethnographic studies suggest that militarization has permeated police work, one could argue that such militarization does not necessarily influence the ability of the police to conduct their work effectively or the public's perception of police overall. Indeed Williams and Westall (2003) found that PPU officers were no more likely

