to use force than were non‐PPU officers, though their sample was limited to 3 years of data from one LEA. However, in a study predating much of the militarization debate, Bell (1982) found that public interactions with police can vary with displays of militarization. Using an experimental design, Bell collected 2,587 observations of civilian–police interactions with police wearing either civilian style blazers and slacks or more military styled uniforms, while also assigning officers to be either informal and friendly or more formal and authoritarian in demeanor. Results from this experiment found that police interactions with civilians were more positive when police adopted informal attitudes and non‐militaristic uniforms than when police are in militaristic uniforms using authoritarian attitudes. Similarly, Mummolo (2018) conducted an experimental assessment of public attitudes toward militarized police using online surveys to emulate experiential exposure to police. Mummolo exposed 1,566 survey takers to different news images of police with different levels of militarization on display (e.g., wearing patrol uniforms afoot vs. wearing riot gear and with armored vehicles) and generally found that respondents exposed to images of police with military weapons and vehicles had less support for police issues than were those exposed to less militaristic images. While Bell and Mummolo both offer caveats about the generalizability of their experiments, these experimental approaches offer promise for continued research on police militarization's effect on public perceptions of police.
Finally, in a quasi‐experimental study, Phillips, Wheeler, and Kim (2016) used neighborhood data from Buffalo, New York, to assess the treatment effect of PPU raids on neighborhood crime rates. Using propensity score matching to compare neighborhoods that experienced a PPU raid to those that did not, Phillips et al. (2016) found that PPU raids only temporarily reduced crime rates and may have actually increased calls for police service. Recent work by Mummolo (2018) supports these findings. In addition to his experimental study, Mummolo also examined the creation and deployment of PPUs in Maryland from 2010 to 2014, finding that PPU use did not reduce crime rates or violence against police officers in LEA jurisdictions where they were used and that PPUs were more likely to be deployed in locations with more Black residents. Using national‐level data from the Census of State and Local Law Enforcement agencies to assess the presence and creation of SWAT teams in 8,961 LEAs in 2000, 2004, and 2008, Mummolo again found no association between the presence of SWAT teams in a LEA and crime rates or violence against police officers. In short, the findings from experimental work on PPUs and police militarization suggest that the public generally reacts negatively to images of police militarization while the deployment of PPUs as a militarized police tactic appears to have a negligible effect on crime rates.

4.3 | Ecological studies of police militarization
The final area of police militarization studies we review here focuses on ecological studies of police militarization using government data on the acquisition of military hardware by LEAs to indicate police militarization efforts. Such ecological studies were largely infeasible until fairly recently. LEAs are not regularly required to provide statistics on PPUs or military hardware to traditional data sources that criminologists and sociologists regularly turn to (e.g., the Uniform Crime Reports or the Law Enforcement Management and Administrative Statistics survey). Consequently, there have been few efforts to examine how locality specific measures of police militarization might be associated with other demographic trends (such as racial demographics, poverty, or even crime rates). Indeed, the only study we are aware of is Jackson and Carroll's (1981) assessment of police expenditures that included grant monies from the Law Enforcement Assistance Administration (LEAA) to purchase some military equipment.1 While Jackson and Carroll found that police expenditures on equipment and personnel were associated with a curvilinear racial threat dynamic (Blalock, 1967), their analysis did not account for militarized equipment specifically and was limited to LEAA data from 1971 to 1974. This area of work has grown rapidly though with the increasing quality of data available from the Department of Defense's (DoD) 1033 Program.
The 1033 Program is the institutional successor to the 1208 Program originally created under the National Defense Authorization Act (NDAA) of 1990 (both programs got their inventive titles because they were created under Sections 1033 and 1208 of the NDAA). Prior to 1997, the 1208 Program provided surplus DoD hardware

