STEIDLEY AND RAMEY

to LEAs for drug interdiction efforts, but after 1997, the NDAA was renewed and a revised Section 1033 now allowed DoD surplus to be issued to LEAs for “bona fide law enforcement purposes that assist in their arrest and apprehension mission” (Defense Logistics Agency, 2016). In recent years, journalists have fixated on LEA acquisition of military equipment such as armored vehicles and battle rifles via the 1033 Program, but the majority of equipment provided by the 1033 Program is non‐combat gear such as medical supplies, office furniture, and miscellaneous items like guitars. LEA applications for the 1033 Program supplies do not require distinctions between combat and non‐ combat gear, and once a request is approved, the only financial cost to LEAs in is shipping charges (Bruce, Carruthers, Harris, Murray, & Park, 2017; Harris, Park, Bruce, & Murray, 2017). While LEAs may purchase military equipment using their own funds or grant monies (including from Department of Homeland Security grants) (Parlapiano, 2014), the 1033 Program is unique because it has a lower level of oversight and is less expensive than alternative approaches (Bove & Gavrilova, 2017; Department of Homeland Security 2018). Research on police militarization has grown rapidly, as the DoD has increased the quality of data reported from the 1033 Program in recent years. This includes reports on the types of military equipment sent to requesting LEAs, the dollar value of that equipment, and identifier codes that allow researchers to link the 1033 Program data on military hardware to common datasets used in ecological studies, including the Census Bureau datasets and the Uniform Crime Reports (Ramey & Steidley, 2018). However, there remain limitations to the 1033 data, as the data lack historical coverage of LEA acquisition of DoD supplies during the earliest years of the program and many supplies not considered “controlled” by the DoD are not tracked after 1 year post‐transfer (see Lawson, 2018, and Mummolo, 2018, for more information on these limitations).
While much of the previous research on police militarization has focused on exploring the creation of PPUs and the cultural influences of militarization on police work (Kraska, 2007), research using the 1033 Program data has focused more on macro‐level determinants of social control and their influence on the 1033 Program participation by LEAs. Ajilore (2015) found in a cross‐sectional study that county‐level acquisitions of mine‐resistant ambush protected (MRAP) armored vehicles by LEAs were associated with higher levels of racial segregation in counties but not with higher levels of overall minority group presence. Similarly, Burkhardt and Baker (2018) merged 1033 data on LEA acquisition of MRAPs with data from the Law Enforcement Management and Administrative Statistics survey (LEMAS) and found that LEAs serving larger Black populations were less likely to acquire an MRAP. Burkhardt and Baker also find that LEAs that embodied tenants of militarism (i.e., possessed SWAT teams and mandated officers to wear body armor) and used civil asset forfeitures were more likely to acquire to MRAPS. They argued that police who seek military equipment may view the public they serve as both a threat to officer safety and an opportunity to secure a LEA fiscal resources (Burkhardt & Baker, 2018). Radil, Dezzani, and McAden (2017) also examined the 1033 Program data to find that local geographies likely influence the 1033 Program participation. Ramey and Steidley (2018) examined minority group threat accounts using the LEA‐level information on the percentage of population that is either Black or Hispanic and disaggregated monetary values on the 1033 Program materials obtained into either militarized equipment (e.g., firearms, armored vehicles, and night vision goggles) and non‐militarized equipment (e.g., passenger cars, office supplies, and tents). Ramey and Steidley found that racial threat patterns emerged for LEAs acquiring militarized equipment but not for non‐militarized equipment, supporting the idea that police militarization is in part a response to racial threat dynamics in the United States (Liska, 1992; Stults & Baumer, 2007). Ramey and Steidley also found that efforts by LEAs to obtain militarized equipment were associated with higher violent crime rates but not with violence against police officers or terror attacks, offering mixed support for the idea that police militarization is pursued to improve public and police safety.
While some of the above studies examining the determinants of the 1033 Program participation have emphasized the importance of race, another vein of research has examined the effect of the 1033 Program participation as an independent variable influencing other socioeconomic factors. Bove and Gavrilova (2017) use the 1033 Program data on the number of items from LEAs received from 2007 to 2012, aggregated to the county level, to test the effect of the 1033 Program acquisitions on crime rates and found that increases in acquisitions were associated with reductions in violent crime. Importantly though, Bove and Gavrilova note that the 1033 Program acquisitions for vehicles

