11 of 16

or weapons had the smallest marginal impact on crime rates and that acquisitions of non‐military gear had larger impacts. In a similar study, Harris et al. (2017), using the county‐level 1033 Program data on the value of weapons, vehicles, and optical gear obtained by LEAs from 1997 to 2012, found that counties obtaining greater monetary values of tactical military gear had fewer police assaults and deaths, increased drug arrests, and fewer complaints against officers.2 Bruce et al. (2017) examined the effect of the 1033 Program acquisitions on local government spending, finding that increases in the value of supplies obtained from the 1033 Program did not crowd out local government spending on crime control, which may suggest that the 1033 Program supplies are a valuable boost to local crime control resources. Finally, in an assessment of the state‐level 1033 Program participation, McQuoid and Vitt (2017) found a negative association between the state‐level value of the 1033 Program equipment obtained and state‐level suicide rates.3 Such findings suggest that the 1033 Program participation has beneficial outcomes in crime control and public health. However, we would caution that establishing causality between the 1033 Program participation and reduced crimes rates remains elusive in part because county‐level studies likely suffer from missing data on crime reporting at the county level (Maltz, 2006; Maltz & Targonski, 2002) and crime rates from 1995 to the present have declined (perhaps independently) while participation in the 1033 Program increased (Rosenfeld, 2004).
Other studies of the 1033 Program participation suggest more detrimental impacts though. Insler, McMurrey, and McQuoid (2016) examined family‐level charitable giving using data from the 2001–2013 U.S. Panel Study of Income Dynamics and found that state‐level increases in the value of the 1033 Program materials issued to LEAs reduced charitable donations made by Black families but not those made by White families. Insler et al. suggest that such findings may indicate that the 1033 Program participation has a negative effect on social solidarity in the United States. Delehanty et al. (2017) used county‐level data on police killings of civilians and dogs in Connecticut, Maine, Nevada, and New Hampshire in 2013 to find a positive association between the 1033 Program participation and police violence. Lawson (2018) conducted a similar study using a sample of all LEAs that participated in the 1033 Program and found that increases in the value of the 1033 Program materials obtained were associated with increases in the LEA‐ level counts of police killings but not with increases in the odds of a police killing occurring. Such findings suggest that increases in police militarization via the acquisition of DoD materials may produce social harms in the form of both overpolicing and reducing social solidarity in communities, which can contribute to criminogenic conditions (Peterson & Krivo, 2010).

5 | THE STATE OF RESEARCH ON POLICE MILITARIZATION
In reviewing the above literature, we can draw some insights across these different findings. Qualitative and ethnographic studies have demonstrated that current police work values militarism and often views militarized police practices (such as the use of military equipment in police work and PPUs) as professional practices (Kraska, 1996; Phillips, 2016, 2018). These positive views of militarism in police work have emerged in part because norms in police work view martial efficiency as fundamental to being a “real cop” who fights crime and comes home safe at the end of the day along with traditional norms of masculinity (Kraska, 1996; Kraska & Paulsen, 1997; Phillips, 2016). Contrary to public debates that have emerged since the events in Ferguson, such norms and practices that make police militarization attractive to police are not new, and many police feel that public skepticism of police militarization is misguided (Phillips, 2018). Furthermore, different aspects of police militarization have always existed in the American police to some extent. For example, the channeling of federal funds to provide military gear and training to local police has existed in some form since the 1960s (Hinton, 2016; Jackson & Carroll, 1981), though it was revamped with the war on drugs (Kraska & Kappeler, 1997) and the war on terror (Kraska, 2007).
Though the police often view police militarization favorably, and as the federal government continues to facilitate the transfer of military equipment to the police, there is little support for the idea that militarization improves police work or criminal justice outcomes (Mummolo, 2018; Phillips et al., 2016). While two ecological studies suggest that the 1033 Program participation is associated with reduced crime rates at the county level, the effect of military

12 of 16

STEIDLEY AND RAMEY

equipment is weak and causality remains questionable (Bove & Gavrilova, 2017; Harris et al., 2017). At the same time, ecological studies find that factors like racial demographics and militaristic department policies influence some militarizing behaviors from LEAs (Burkhardt & Baker, 2018; Jackson & Carroll, 1981; Ramey & Steidley, 2018), while studies of actual PPU use suggest militarized police operations have little effect on crime and do not improve overall officer safety (Mummolo, 2018; Phillips et al., 2016). In fact, police militarization may negatively impact the public's perceptions of the police to the point that citizens are more hostile toward the police (Bell, 1982; Mummolo, 2018). This is especially concerning given that the public's support of police militarization is strongly influenced by preexisting perceptions of police legitimacy (Moule, Burruss, et al., 2018; Moule, Fox, & Parry, 2018). However, it remains unknown how actual levels of police militarization impact public perceptions of police legitimacy. These findings illustrate the importance of conceptualizing police militarization in a manner that allows researchers to distinguish between the effects of police militarization in the material dimension (i.e., the acquisition of military equipment) and the operations dimension (i.e., the actual use of military tactics and training) (Kraska, 2007). Future research should continue to assess how variability in police militarization across the different dimensions of police work might impact criminal justice outcomes.
Assessing the impact of police militarization is important beyond crime control. Some indicators of police militarization appear to be associated with racialized trends in policing as opposed to actual threats to police (Ajilore, 2015; Mummolo, 2018; Ramey & Steidley, 2018) as well as with the increased the use of lethal force by the police (Delehanty et al., 2017; Lawson, 2018). Research also suggests that the public interactions with and perceptions of police who display signs of militarism are less amiable (Bell, 1982; Mummolo, 2018). Such findings are troubling given that police continue to view militarization as a desirable practice given the lack of positive findings linking police militarization to improved criminal justice outcomes (Phillips, 2018; Turner & Fox, 2017). As such, a concerning possibility emerges. People with low perceptions of police legitimacy tend to be skeptical of police militarization, yet police often think militarization is efficacious and that skepticism of police militarization is misguided. In the event that localities were demand for police services are high, yet police legitimacy is low, police militarization may be a response that local police believe would improve public safety while unintentionally harming public perceptions of police legitimacy and may be implemented more often against minorities.
Given the nature of modern criminal justice administration to orient organizational decisions around metrics like crimes reported to the police, arrests made, and police officers killed or assaulted (Feeley & Simon, 1992; Garland, 2001), police will likely continue to pursue militarization so long as the negative aspects of militarization are not immediately observed by the police. Unfortunately, many of these negative aspects are not included in traditional criminal justice data collection efforts, making it a challenge for scholars to quantitatively link detrimental community outcomes to militarization. While studies of the 1033 Program have begun to change this trend, we would encourage researchers to also look beyond just the material dimension of police militarization, as experimental studies have done (Mummolo, 2018; Phillips et al., 2016).
It should be noted that none of the mentioned studies or arguments implicate that police work should become completely decoupled from militarism. As long as the police remain permitted to use force, militarism in police work will continue to have some value. As Kraska (1999) notes, extreme events like mass shootings hostage situations can call for extreme force from the police. Likewise, having officers train to charge toward danger rather than away from it is undeniably beneficial for civil society. The concerns most often raised about police militarization though are not about the use of militarized police units, equipment, or tactics to respond to extreme events. Rather, concern most often centers on the increased use of military equipment and tactics in day‐to‐day police work and the potential for adverse effects (i.e., the use of PPUs to serve drug warrants or do routine patrol work, or whether police might start viewing citizens as combatants (Meeks, 2006)). Indeed, despite popular appearances, modern doctrines of police work do little to preclude the use of militarized police units in “community policing” or “hot spot policing” strategies (DeMichele & Kraska, 2001). Until researchers or LEAs collect more data on police practices and the use of militarized tactics and/or equipment, it will remain difficult to empirically assess if militarization negatively impacts routine police work at the macro‐level and if less militarized approaches can produce similar or better outcomes for both the police and the public.

