At the same time, we encourage scholars to continue engaging with the normative debates that have always been central to the police militarization literature. Fundamentally, we feel it is important for academics to interrogate the role of state power in a free society and not immediately accept the idea that “professionalization” of police work is tantamount to militarization. We also feel such arguments are not an attack on police or law enforcement officials. Real improvements in public safety can come from increasing the legitimacy of the police and criminal justice institutions (Tyler, 2004, 2006). However, research suggests militarization can hinder public perceptions of the police (Bell, 1982; Mummolo, 2018) and that populations skeptical of police legitimacy are least supportive of militarization (Moule, Burruss, et al., 2018). Thus, social scientists have an obligation to continue engaging other scholars and criminal justice practitioners about both the benefits and false promises of police militarization for crime control. Academics and practitioners alike must continue to engage each other in this field to improve both the quality of police work and community outcomes.
